  <content>
    <title>Docker LLM Prompts</title>

    <summary>Parameterized LLM prompt templates for the full range of Docker tasks: generating production Dockerfiles, optimizing existing ones, auditing for security, debugging container failures, integrating CI/CD scanning, and designing multi-container architectures. Fill in the bracketed variables and submit to any capable model.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Docker tasks map cleanly to LLM capabilities: generating boilerplate from requirements, translating single-stage to multi-stage builds, listing security issues with severity, and producing Kubernetes manifests from Compose files. Prompt templates encode the output format and checklist so the model covers the full surface without omissions. Each template targets a different task scope — generation, optimization, security, troubleshooting — so the agent picks the minimum scope needed rather than dumping a combined mega-prompt.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Generating a new Dockerfile for a language/framework combination not covered by the language templates.</item>
        <item>Auditing an existing Dockerfile against 2025-2026 best practices without reading the full methodology.</item>
        <item>Debugging a container build or runtime failure with structured context.</item>
        <item>Generating CI pipeline steps for Docker build, test, scan, and push.</item>
        <item>Designing multi-container architectures or migrating Docker Compose to Kubernetes.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>When the exact Dockerfile is available in docker-language-templates — use it directly instead of prompting.</item>
        <item>When the LLM output cannot be reviewed before deployment — always validate generated Dockerfiles against the checklist in docker-image-optimization and docker-security-hardening.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="generation-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="generate-production-dockerfile"><![CDATA[
Create a production-ready Dockerfile for a {LANGUAGE} application with these requirements:

Application: {APP_DESCRIPTION}
Framework: {FRAMEWORK}
Entry point: {ENTRY_POINT}
Port: {PORT}
Database: {DATABASE_TYPE} (optional)

Requirements:
1. Multi-stage build to minimize image size
2. Non-root user execution
3. Health check endpoint at /health
4. Proper layer caching optimization
5. No secrets in Dockerfile
6. Security best practices (2025-2026)

Include:
- Appropriate base image selection with pinned version
- Build and production stages
- .dockerignore file
- Explanation of each decision
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="convert-to-multi-stage"><![CDATA[
Convert this single-stage Dockerfile to a multi-stage build:

```dockerfile
{CURRENT_DOCKERFILE}
```

Goals:
1. Separate build and runtime stages
2. Minimize final image size
3. Include only runtime dependencies in the final stage
4. Maintain all functionality

Explain the benefits of each stage and the expected size reduction.
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="generate-docker-compose"><![CDATA[
Create a docker-compose.yml for this architecture:

Services:
{LIST_OF_SERVICES}

Requirements:
- Health checks for all services
- Proper dependency ordering (depends_on with condition: service_healthy)
- Named volumes for persistence
- Resource limits (CPU and memory)
- Environment variable management via env_file
- Network isolation (custom bridge network)

Include both development and production configurations as separate files (docker-compose.yml + docker-compose.prod.yml).
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="optimization-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="optimize-existing-dockerfile"><![CDATA[
Review and optimize this Dockerfile for production use:

```dockerfile
{CURRENT_DOCKERFILE}
```

Check for:
1. Image size optimization (multi-stage builds, base image choice)
2. Security issues (root user, secrets in ENV/ARG, base image vulnerabilities)
3. Layer caching efficiency (instruction order, cache mounts)
4. Build time optimization
5. Health check presence
6. Compliance with 2025-2026 best practices

Provide:
- Optimized Dockerfile with inline comments explaining each change
- Explanation of each change and why it matters
- Estimated size reduction
- List of remaining issues that require application-level changes
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="optimize-build-time"><![CDATA[
My Docker build is slow. Help optimize:

Dockerfile:
```dockerfile
{DOCKERFILE}
```

Current build time: {TIME}
CI/CD platform: {PLATFORM}

Analyze:
1. Layer caching issues (instruction order)
2. Unnecessary operations (redundant copies, full apt upgrades)
3. Network fetches that could be cached
4. Build context size (missing .dockerignore entries)

Provide optimized Dockerfile with expected improvements and the recommended .dockerignore additions.
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="reduce-image-size"><![CDATA[
Help reduce Docker image size:

Current image: {IMAGE_NAME}
Current size: {SIZE}
Target size: {TARGET_SIZE}

Dockerfile:
```dockerfile
{DOCKERFILE}
```

Strategies to explore in order of impact:
1. Base image alternatives (-slim, -alpine, distroless)
2. Multi-stage build improvements
3. Dependency pruning (unused packages, dev dependencies in prod)
4. Static linking for compiled languages
5. Layer squashing (if applicable)

For each strategy, show the change and the expected size reduction.
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="security-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="security-audit"><![CDATA[
Perform a security audit of this Dockerfile:

```dockerfile
{DOCKERFILE}
```

Check for:
1. Base image vulnerabilities (flag if not using -slim/-alpine/distroless)
2. Root user execution (missing USER directive)
3. Secrets exposure (ENV/ARG with secrets, COPY of .env files)
4. Unnecessary packages or build tools in final stage
5. File permissions and ownership
6. Missing HEALTHCHECK
7. Missing .dockerignore indicators

Provide:
- List of issues with severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW/INFO)
- Remediation for each issue
- Fixed Dockerfile
- Runtime flags to add (--cap-drop, --read-only, --security-opt)
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="add-security-hardening"><![CDATA[
Add security hardening to this Dockerfile following 2025-2026 best practices:

```dockerfile
{DOCKERFILE}
```

Add or verify:
1. Non-root user with minimal permissions (useradd -r)
2. Read-only filesystem support (ensure app does not write to rootfs)
3. Capability dropping guidance (runtime flags to document)
4. Secret management pattern (replace any ENV secrets with runtime injection)
5. Image signing setup (DOCKER_CONTENT_TRUST instructions)

Explain each security measure and its threat model.
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="add-ci-scanning"><![CDATA[
Add container security scanning to this CI pipeline:

```yaml
{CURRENT_PIPELINE}
```

Integrate:
- Trivy (vulnerability scanning) — fail on HIGH/CRITICAL CVEs
- Hadolint (Dockerfile linting) — fail on DL3 and SC rules
- SBOM generation (syft or trivy --format cyclonedx)

CI platform: {PLATFORM} (GitHub Actions / GitLab CI / Jenkins)

Configuration requirements:
- Fail build on HIGH/CRITICAL vulnerabilities
- Upload SARIF results to GitHub Code Scanning (if GitHub Actions)
- Store SBOM as build artifact
- Cache scanner databases between runs
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="troubleshooting-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="debug-container-issue"><![CDATA[
Help debug this container issue:

Error: {ERROR_MESSAGE}

Dockerfile:
```dockerfile
{DOCKERFILE}
```

Context:
- Platform: {OS/ARCHITECTURE}
- Docker version: {VERSION}
- Base image: {IMAGE}
- What was tried: {PREVIOUS_ATTEMPTS}

Provide:
1. Root cause analysis
2. Step-by-step fix
3. Prevention measures and documentation to update
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="debug-runtime-failure"><![CDATA[
Container exits immediately after docker run. Help diagnose:

Image: {IMAGE}

docker run output:
```
{OUTPUT}
```

docker logs output:
```
{LOGS}
```

docker inspect (partial):
```json
{INSPECT_JSON}
```

Check for:
1. Entry point or CMD errors
2. Missing environment variables
3. Permission issues (non-root user cannot read files)
4. Network/port binding failures
5. Health check failures causing restart
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="migration-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="migrate-compose-to-kubernetes"><![CDATA[
Create Kubernetes manifests from this Docker Compose:

```yaml
{DOCKER_COMPOSE}
```

Generate:
1. Deployment manifests (one per service)
2. Service manifests (ClusterIP for internal, LoadBalancer/Ingress for external)
3. ConfigMaps for non-secret environment variables
4. Secret templates (placeholder values — do not include real secrets)
5. PersistentVolumeClaims for volumes
6. Ingress (if web-facing services exist)
7. NetworkPolicy for service isolation

Include:
- Resource requests and limits (derived from Compose resource limits)
- Health checks (readiness + liveness probes from Compose healthcheck)
- Rolling update strategy
- Security contexts (runAsNonRoot, readOnlyRootFilesystem)
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="containerize-legacy-app"><![CDATA[
Help containerize this legacy application:

Application: {APP_DESCRIPTION}
Language: {LANGUAGE}
Dependencies: {DEPENDENCIES}
Configuration: {CONFIG_FILES}
Data storage: {DATA_PATHS}
Current deployment: {CURRENT_METHOD}

Provide:
1. Containerization strategy (single container vs. multi-service split)
2. Dockerfile (multi-stage if applicable)
3. Docker Compose (if multi-service)
4. Migration steps in order
5. Potential issues and solutions (file paths, environment variables, port conflicts)
6. Health check implementation for each service
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="architecture-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="review-container-architecture"><![CDATA[
Review this container architecture:

Services:
{SERVICE_LIST}

docker-compose.yml:
```yaml
{COMPOSE}
```

Review for:
1. Service boundary correctness (one responsibility per container)
2. Communication patterns (synchronous vs. asynchronous)
3. Data persistence strategy (volumes, external databases)
4. Scaling bottlenecks (stateful services, shared volumes)
5. Security isolation (network policies, secrets)
6. Monitoring and logging approach (centralized vs. per-container)
7. Missing health checks or restart policies

Provide recommendations with priority (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW) and effort (LOW/MEDIUM/HIGH).
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="design-multi-container-app"><![CDATA[
Design container architecture for:

Application: {APP_DESCRIPTION}
Expected load: {TRAFFIC}
Availability requirements: {SLA}
Team size: {TEAM_SIZE}

Constraints:
{CONSTRAINTS}

Provide:
1. Service breakdown (what runs in each container, why)
2. Container specifications (base image, resource limits, health checks)
3. Communication patterns (REST, gRPC, message queue)
4. Data flow description
5. Scaling strategy (which services scale horizontally, which vertically)
6. docker-compose.yml for development
7. Kubernetes migration path when ready to scale
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-variables-reference">
      <p>Variable reference for all templates above:</p>
      <list>
        <item>{LANGUAGE} — Programming language: Python, Node.js, Go, Rust, Java</item>
        <item>{FRAMEWORK} — Application framework: Django, FastAPI, Express, NestJS, Spring Boot</item>
        <item>{APP_DESCRIPTION} — What the app does: REST API for user management</item>
        <item>{ENTRY_POINT} — Main file or command: main.py, server.js, cmd/server</item>
        <item>{PORT} — Exposed port: 8000, 3000, 8080</item>
        <item>{DATABASE_TYPE} — Database system: PostgreSQL, MongoDB, Redis</item>
        <item>{DOCKERFILE} — Current Dockerfile content (full text)</item>
        <item>{CURRENT_DOCKERFILE} — Existing Dockerfile to optimize or convert</item>
        <item>{COMPOSE} — Docker Compose YAML content (full text)</item>
        <item>{CURRENT_PIPELINE} — Existing CI YAML content (full text)</item>
        <item>{ERROR_MESSAGE} — Build or runtime error message</item>
        <item>{PLATFORM} — CI/CD platform: GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Jenkins</item>
        <item>{REGISTRY} — Container registry: Docker Hub, ECR, GCR, GHCR</item>
        <item>{SIZE} — Current image size: 1.2GB</item>
        <item>{TARGET_SIZE} — Desired image size: less than 200MB</item>
        <item>{LIST_OF_SERVICES} — Service names and descriptions, one per line</item>
        <item>{OUTPUT} — docker run console output</item>
        <item>{LOGS} — docker logs output</item>
        <item>{INSPECT_JSON} — Relevant portion of docker inspect output</item>
        <item>{PREVIOUS_ATTEMPTS} — What has already been tried and failed</item>
      </list>
    </section>

